-- 
Asian Stocks Rise on Commodity Price Gains, Factory Resumptions in Japan

-- B y   S h a n i   R a j a
-- 
2011-03-24T11:13:05Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-23/japanese-stock-futures-rise-on-factory-restarts-oil-australia-advances.html
Asian stocks rose for a third day
this week as commodity prices climbed and some Japanese
manufacturers said they would restart work at factories shut by
the March 11 earthquake and tsunami.  BHP Billiton Ltd. (BHP) , the world’s No. 1 mining company, rose
1.2 percent in Sydney after oil, copper and gold prices advanced
yesterday. Cnooc Ltd.,  China ’s biggest offshore oil producer,
gained 1.8 percent in  Hong Kong  as annual profit surged. Komatsu
Ltd., Japan’s largest maker of construction machinery, climbed
1.4 percent in  Tokyo  after resuming some operations. Korean
carmakers surged in  Seoul  on speculation earnings are improving.  The MSCI Asia Pacific Index rose 0.3 percent to 133.09 as
of 8:08 p.m. in Tokyo. About five stocks advanced for every four
that fell. The gauge last week recorded its biggest weekly drop
since the height of the European debt crisis in May, as Japan
fought to prevent a nuclear disaster at a damaged reactor, and
as tensions escalated in Libya.  “Markets appear to be shifting focus to the ongoing
improvement in the macro-economic backdrop in spite of the
ongoing Middle-East turmoil, higher  oil prices  and uncertainties
over  Europe ,” said Nader Naeimi, a Sydney-based strategist at
AMP Capital Investors Ltd., which manages about $98 billion.
“Commodities-related stocks should benefit.”  Japan’s  Nikkei 225 (NKY)  Stock Average slipped 0.2 percent, while
 South Korea ’s Kospi Index gained 1.2 percent.  Australia ’s
S&P/ASX 200 Index rose 1 percent and Hong Kong’s Hang Seng Index
advanced 0.4 percent.  ‘Calming Down’  Futures on the Standard & Poor’s 500 Index climbed 0.5
percent today. The index advanced 0.3 percent yesterday in  New
York  after higher metal prices boosted commodity producers and
 Wells Fargo & Co . said government data showing a record-low pace
in new-home sales will likely be revised higher.  “The nuclear issues don’t allow for optimism, but things
are calming down to some extent, so investors’ intention to
avoid risks is easing,” said  Mitsushige Akino , who oversees
about $450 million in Tokyo at Ichiyoshi Investment Management
Co. “I expect commodity-related stocks will rise on higher
prices.”  The MSCI Asia Pacific Index lost 3.6 percent this year
through yesterday, compared with a gain of 3.2 percent by the
 S&P 500  and a drop of 1 percent by the Stoxx Europe 600 Index.
Stocks in the Asian benchmark are valued at 13.3 times estimated
earnings on average, compared with 13.4 times for the S&P 500
and 11 times for the Stoxx 600.  Copper, Oil  BHP Billiton gained 1.2 percent to A$44.71 in Sydney. Rio
Tinto Group, the world’s second-largest mining company by sales,
advanced 1.1 percent to A$81.60.  Newcrest Mining Ltd. (NCM) ,
Australia’s No. 1 gold producer, increased 2.6 percent to
A$38.05. Aluminum Corp. of China Ltd., the nation’s largest
supplier of the metal, gained 0.8 percent to HK$7.30 in Hong
Kong.  The London Metal Exchange Index of prices for six
industrial metals including copper and aluminum jumped 2.3
percent yesterday to a three-week high. Gold rose for the sixth
straight session yesterday, nearing a record in New York.  Crude oil for May delivery rose 0.7 percent to $105.75 a
barrel in New York yesterday, the highest settlement since Sept.
26, 2008, while the Baltic Dry Index of shipping rates for
commodities advanced 1.4 percent, the biggest increase in seven
days.  Cnooc gained 1.8 percent to HK$18.78 in Hong Kong. China’s
biggest offshore oil producer plans to start new fields at home
and add assets abroad after its fastest output growth boosted
annual profit by 85 percent.  Libya Fighting  Woodside Petroleum Ltd. (WPL) , Australia’s second-largest oil and
gas producer, climbed 1.3 percent to A$45.56 in Sydney.  Caltex
Australia Ltd. (CTX) , the country’s No. 1 oil refiner, plunged 5.3
percent to A$15.31 after saying higher crude prices reduced its
refining margins.  U.S. and allied warplanes continued to strike Muammar Qaddafi’s ground forces as coalition nations neared agreement to
have NATO assume operational control. Libyan government forces
increased their attacks on cities, killing 16 people yesterday
in embattled Misrata and six in the nearby coastal town of
Zentan, opposition spokesman Abdulhafid Ghoga said at a news
conference in Benghazi.  Komatsu climbed 1.4 percent to 2,670 yen in Tokyo. Taiheiyo
Cement Corp. rose 5.2 percent to 161 yen. Denki Kagaku Kogyo
K.K., a maker of chemical products, jumped 3.5 percent to 380
yen after Daiwa Securities Group Inc. raised its rating on the
company.  Supply Disruptions  Japan ’s government said yesterday it estimates the damage
from this month’s record earthquake and tsunami will be as much
as 25 trillion yen ($309 billion), almost four times the bill
faced by the U.S. from Hurricane Katrina.  The destruction will push down the total value of gross
domestic product by as much as 2.75 trillion yen for the year
starting April 1, the government said. The figure, about 0.5
percent of the 530 trillion-yen economy, reflects a decline in
production from supply disruptions and damage to corporate
facilities, without taking into account the effects of possible
power outages.  Engineers at Japan’s damaged nuclear plant today resumed
work on reconnecting power as Tokyo authorities prepared to hand
out bottled water to families after determining that tap water
may be unsafe for babies.  Hyundai Motor Co., South Korea’s biggest automaker, rose
4.2 percent to 198,500 won in Seoul and affiliate  Kia Motors
Corp. (000270)  advanced 3.4 percent to 66,900 won. Yoon Pil Joong, an
analyst with Samsung Securities Co., said the companies will
post “solid” first-quarter earnings.  “Investors’ confidence in their earnings is continuing to
boost shares,” Yoon said by phone today. “Their March car
sales are likely to turn out good.” Hyundai Mobis Co., a parts
supplier to automakers, gained 5.7 percent to 308,500 won.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Shani Raja in Sydney at 
